7. Part 1 — Make the Shell Feel Fast

“This first section is about getting more comfortable in the shell.

These are small keyboard shortcuts and habits that make the command line feel less clunky. Once they become muscle memory, they save a lot of time.”

⸻

8. Command-Line Editing Shortcuts

“These shortcuts help when you’re editing a command you already typed.

Instead of holding the arrow key or deleting everything manually, you can jump around and cut parts of the line quickly.

Ctrl+A jumps to the beginning of the line, Ctrl+E jumps to the end, Ctrl+U cuts everything before the cursor, and Ctrl+K cuts everything after the cursor.”

Demo line:
“I’ll type a long command and show how quickly I can move around it. I’ll use Ctrl+A to jump to the beginning, Ctrl+E to jump back to the end, Ctrl+U to clear the line, and Ctrl+Y to paste it back.”

Transition:
“The point is that the shell already has editing tools built in, so we do not always need to retype the command.”

⸻

9. More Shell Movement Shortcuts

“These are a few more shortcuts that are useful when a command is long or when something is running.

Alt+B and Alt+F move backward and forward by word. Ctrl+C stops a running command. Ctrl+D exits the current shell or ends input.

One useful command to pair with this is echo $?, which shows the exit code from the last command.”

Demo line:
“I’ll run sleep 60, then stop it with Ctrl+C. After that, I’ll run echo $?. A zero usually means success, and a non-zero value means the command failed, was interrupted, or returned some other status.”

Transition:
“That little exit code can be useful when you’re troubleshooting or writing scripts.”

⸻

10. The Magic Last Argument Trick

“This is one of my favorite shortcuts because it feels like magic the first time you use it.

Esc + . or Alt + . inserts the last argument from the previous command. That is really useful when the last thing you typed was a path, a filename, or a service name.”

Demo line:
“I’ll create a directory with mkdir -p /tmp/rhel-demo/logs. Now instead of retyping that path, I’ll type cd, press Esc then ., and Bash inserts the path for me.”

Transition:
“This is especially helpful with long paths, because long paths are easy to mistype.”

⸻

11. Command History Tricks

“This slide is about reusing work you already did.

history shows previous commands. !! reruns the previous command. sudo !! reruns the previous command with sudo. !$ grabs the last argument from the previous command, and !* grabs all the arguments.”

Demo line:
“I’ll run a simple command, then use !! to run it again. Then I’ll show !$, which grabs just the last argument from the previous command.”

Transition:
“A lot of command-line work is repeating something with one small change, and these shortcuts help with that.”

⸻

12. Fix the Last Command Without Retyping

“This one is useful when the last command was almost right, but one word needs to change.

The ^old^new syntax reruns the previous command and replaces the first matching word.”

Demo line:
“I’ll use echo so this is safe. I’ll run echo systemctl start firewalld.service. Then I’ll type ^start^stop. Bash reruns the previous command, but swaps start for stop.”

Transition:
“In real troubleshooting, this saves time when the command is long and only one piece needs to change.”

⸻

13. Reverse History Search

“Reverse history search is another way to avoid retyping.

Press Ctrl+R, type part of a previous command, and Bash searches backward through your command history. You do not need to remember the full command. You only need to remember one unique word.”

Demo line:
“I’ll press Ctrl+R and type firewall. Bash brings up a previous command that had firewall in it. If I press Ctrl+R again, it keeps cycling through older matches.”

Transition:
“When I find the command I want, I can run it as-is or edit it first.”

⸻

14. Page Up / Page Down History Search

“Page Up and Page Down are another useful history feature on RHEL.

If I type the beginning of a command, like systemctl, and press Page Up, it cycles through previous commands that started with systemctl.

That is different from the Up Arrow, because the Up Arrow walks through command history one command at a time.”

Demo line:
“I’ll type systemctl and press Page Up. Now it is pulling previous systemctl commands from history. I can keep pressing Page Up to go farther back, or Page Down to move forward through the matches.”

Transition:
“This is helpful when you remember the command family, but not the exact command.”

⸻

15. Tree — See the Directory Layout at a Glance

“tree is useful when you want to quickly understand a directory layout.

ls gives you a flat list, but tree shows the structure visually. I like tree -L 2 because it limits the output to two levels, so you get a useful view without flooding the screen.”

Demo line:
“I’ll run tree -L 2 /tmp/rhel-demo. That gives us a quick visual of what is under that directory. If I only want directories, I can use tree -d.”

Transition:
“This is also useful when you are explaining a folder structure to someone else.”

⸻

16. Directory Navigation Basics

“This slide covers basic navigation.

cd - is one of the most useful ones because it takes you back to the previous directory. pwd tells you where you are. realpath, dirname, and basename are useful when you’re working with full paths and want to break them apart.”

Demo line:
“I’ll move into a nested path, run pwd, then use cd .. and cd ../.. to move up. Then I’ll use cd - to jump back. After that, I’ll show realpath, dirname, and basename on a file path.”

Transition:
“The main idea is to let the shell help you manage paths instead of retyping everything.”

⸻

17. Directory Stack

“cd - is great when you are switching between two directories.

But when you are jumping between multiple locations, pushd, popd, and dirs are better. Think of it like a directory stack that Bash remembers for you.”

Demo line:
“I’ll run pushd /var/log, then pushd /etc/ssh, then pushd /tmp. Now dirs -v shows the stack. When I run popd, Bash moves me back through the saved locations.”

Transition:
“This is useful during troubleshooting because you often jump between logs, config files, and temporary work areas.”

⸻

18. Tab Completion

“Tab completion is one of the easiest ways to save time and avoid typos.

If I start typing a path, command, service name, or file name and press Tab, Bash can complete it or show possible matches.”

Demo line:
“I’ll type cd /var/lo and press Tab, and it completes /var/log. I can also try something like systemctl status ssh and press Tab to complete service names.”

Transition:
“The big point is: do not type full names if the shell can safely complete them for you.”

⸻

19. Help Without Leaving the Terminal

“This slide is about finding help quickly without leaving the terminal.

Good admins do not memorize everything. They know how to find the right answer quickly. command --help is usually good for quick syntax, and man pages are better when you need more detail.”

Demo line:
“I’ll open man systemctl, then search inside the man page using /--failed. Inside a man page, / searches, n goes to the next match, and q quits.”

Transition:
“I can also use man -k firewall or apropos selinux when I know the topic but not the exact command.”

