21. Aliases and Functions

“Aliases let you save short names for commands you type often.

For example, ports can run ss -tulpen, and failed can run systemctl list-units --failed. Functions are better when you need arguments or a little bit of logic.”

Demo line:
“I’ll define an alias called ports, then use type ports to show what it expands to. Then I’ll run it. I’ll also show a small function called mkcd, which creates a directory and moves into it.”

Transition:
“That is a good example of when a function is better than an alias, because it uses an argument.”

