24. Systemctl Service Basics

“systemctl is one of the first places we usually go when checking services.

status tells us what the service is doing. start, stop, restart, and reload control the service. enable --now is useful because it enables a service at boot and starts it immediately.”

Demo line:
“I’ll check systemctl status firewalld --no-pager. For the start, stop, and restart examples, I’ll show them with echo so I’m not changing service state during the demo.”

Transition:
“The safe habit here is to check status before restarting something.”

⸻

25. Systemctl Triage Commands

“This slide is about service triage.

systemctl list-units --failed is one of the quickest checks because it shows failed units right away. is-active and is-enabled are useful because they are script-friendly and return meaningful exit codes.”

Demo line:
“I’ll run systemctl list-units --failed --no-pager. Then I’ll run systemctl is-active firewalld and echo $? so you can see the exit code.”

Transition:
“The command output is useful for people, and the exit code is useful for scripts.”

⸻

26. Journalctl Superpower

“journalctl lets us filter logs instead of reading everything.

That is the big takeaway. We can filter by service, boot, time, priority, and we can follow logs live.”

Demo line:
“I’ll run journalctl -u sshd -b --since "1 hour ago" --no-pager. That gives me logs for one service, from this boot, within a time window.”

Transition:
“The idea is to ask the logs a focused question instead of scrolling through a huge file hoping to spot the issue.”

⸻

27. Quick Log Review

“This slide covers classic log tools: less, tail, and grep.

less is good for reading and searching a file. tail -f is good when you want to watch new log lines come in. grep helps pull out the lines that match what you care about.”

Demo line:
“I’ll open a demo log with less, search for ERROR, and use n and N to move between matches. Then I’ll show tail -f and append a new line from another tab so you can see it update live.”

Transition:
“After that, grep -A and grep -B help show context around the matching lines.”

⸻

28. Grep Tricks

“grep becomes much more useful when you add options.

-i ignores case, -n shows line numbers, -r searches recursively, and -A, -B, or -C show context around a match.”

Demo line:
“I’ll search the demo log for error, show line numbers with -n, and show context with -C2. Then I’ll use grep -Ev '^#|^$' to hide comments and blank lines in a config file.”

Transition:
“That makes config files much easier to review.”

⸻

29. Find Files Without Guessing

“find helps when you do not know exactly where something is.

You can search by name, type, size, modified time, owner, permissions, and then run another command on the results.”

Demo line:
“I’ll use find under /tmp/rhel-demo so this is safe. I’ll find recently modified files, config files, and larger files.”

Transition:
“The safety habit here is important: use -print first so you can review the results before doing anything destructive like -delete.”

⸻

30. Xargs

“xargs takes a list and feeds it into another command.

A common pattern is: find creates the list, and xargs runs a command against each item in that list.”

Demo line:
“I’ll find log files, then pipe them into xargs grep to search for errors. Then I’ll show the safer version using -print0 and xargs -0, which handles unusual filenames better.”

Transition:
“The main idea is that xargs connects one command’s output to another command’s input.”

⸻

31. Awk

“awk is useful when the answer is hiding in columns.

You can print specific fields, filter rows based on field values, and do quick summaries. It can look intimidating, but the simple uses are very approachable.”

Demo line:
“I’ll start with awk '{print $1}' against an access log to print the client IPs. Then I’ll pipe that into sort, uniq -c, and sort -nr to count repeated IPs.”

Transition:
“That pattern is really useful for summarizing log data.”

⸻

32. Sed

“sed is useful for quick text edits and quick text filtering.

I like to teach it in two stages: first, preview the change in the output only. Then, if you need to edit the file, use -i.bak so you get a backup.”

Demo line:
“I’ll run sed 's/8080/9090/' against a demo config so we can see the replacement without changing the file. Then I’ll show sed -n '1,5p' to print only certain lines.”

Transition:
“Finally, I’ll make a safe copy and use sed -i.bak, then show the backup.”

