33. Watch

“watch turns a normal command into a live dashboard.

It reruns the command every few seconds. This is useful when you’re waiting for a service, port, disk state, or firewall state to change.”

Demo line:
“I’ll run watch -n 2 date first because it is simple and you can see it refresh. Then I’ll stop it with Ctrl+C.”

Transition:
“A more practical example would be watching df -h, failed units, or a port check.”

⸻

34. Process Monitoring

“top is the classic process monitor.

It may not be pretty, but it is usually available. ps is good when you want a quick sorted list, like top memory or CPU users. pgrep and pidof help locate processes by name.”

Demo line:
“I’ll open top and use a few keys: P to sort by CPU, M to sort by memory, c to show full command lines, and q to quit.”

Transition:
“Then I’ll show ps aux --sort=-%mem | head and ps aux --sort=-%cpu | head for quick one-line checks.”

⸻

35. btop

“btop is a friendlier dashboard-style process and resource monitor.

Where top can feel like a spreadsheet, btop gives a more visual view of CPU, memory, disks, network, and processes.”

Demo line:
“I’ll open btop if it is available on the lab system. The main thing I want to show is how quickly you can see CPU, memory, disk, network, and process activity in one place.”

Transition:
“I still treat this as a visibility tool first. I do not kill processes unless I understand what owns them and what depends on them.”

⸻

36. Cockpit Web Console

“Cockpit is a web-based RHEL management console.

It gives a visual view of system health, services, logs, storage, networking, accounts, and updates if enabled. I think of it as a useful visibility tool, not a replacement for command-line troubleshooting.”

Demo line:
“I’ll check systemctl status cockpit.socket, then show the URL format: https://server-name:9090.”

Transition:
“The command line still matters because it is scriptable, repeatable, and usually what we use for deeper troubleshooting.”

