44. Safer Command Habits

“These habits are small, but they prevent big mistakes.

Use --dry-run when available. Use sed -i.bak instead of editing with no backup. Use find ... -print before -delete. Check service status before restarting. Use temporary firewall rules first. And avoid putting secrets into commands, because shell history can save them.”

Demo line:
“I’ll show a few examples under /tmp/rhel-demo. The important idea is that the safe version of the command is usually only slightly longer than the risky version.”

⸻

45. Safety Examples

“This slide puts the safety habits into examples.

Before deleting files, print what would be deleted. Before editing a config, make a backup. Before syncing files, use rsync --dry-run.”

Demo line:
“I’ll run a find command with -print first, then show what the delete command would look like. Then I’ll make a dated backup copy of a config file. Finally, I’ll run rsync --dry-run so we can preview the sync without changing anything.”

Transition:
“The key rule is: do not make the first command the destructive command.”

